On Aug 8, 2014, at 10&#58;56 AM, Open Science Grid FootPrints &#60;osg@....&#62; wrote&#58;

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; [Duplicate message snipped]</font></pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='22049#1407513407'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-08-08T15:56:47+00:00">Aug 8, 2014 03:56 PM UTC</time> by <b>Soichi Hayashi</b><a class="anchor" name="1407513407">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>For 1), OIM is currently configured to make request with sha256 hash with all Digicert API. I don&#39;t know of any plan to revert to sha1, so I have no objection to this plan.

For 2), I just confirmed that I am seeing the DigiCertGridTrustCAG2 in my  /etc/grid-security/certificates distributed by OSG. Is there a plan to make the G2 CA available for Digicert-Pilot? Currently it&#39;s not listed in <a href='http&#58;//www.digicert-grid.com/' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//www.digicert-grid.com/</a> If there is, and if Digicert can start issuing pilot certs with G2 CA, then we can test to make sure that nothing is missed.

Soichi</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='22049#1407512652'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-08-08T15:44:12+00:00">Aug 8, 2014 03:44 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1407512652">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>It is now time to complete our transition to SHA-2 certs, which we earlier decided to postpone this until after June 2014.  What this means is that&#58;

1) DigiCert will reject any cert request with a sha-1 algorithm.
2) DigiCert will start using an intermediate CA that the CA certificate itself is signed with SHA-2 algorithm.

About 1, we have been giving out SHA-1 certs to our users by default for a while. So, this change has minimum impact on our systems and our users. A potential although unlikely problem is if OIM code requests a certificate with hash&#39; = &#39;sha1&#39; then we will get an error message from Digicert. Since OIM code already uses sha-2 as its default, this is unlikely, but it is better to double check.

About 2, this is a change in the intermediate CA itself. DigiCert created a new intermediate CA that has the sha-2 hash. The new CA cert has been inn IGTF distribution since April and been released to OSG production on April 8th. Resources having a CA distribution newer or equal to 3.2.8 and 3.1.32 already have the necessary trust roots. If a resource has an older CA distribution, then they will not be able to work with new certificates issued by this intermediate CA. This change has no impact on the way our users requests certificates or our users certificate DN. We expect no action from our users. We expect our resource providers to update their certificate distribution.

With this ticket, I intend to start the change request process with DigiCert to 1) turn off the sha-1 capability and 2) installing the new sha-2 compliant intermediate CA.

Operations team&#58; please tell us whether you approve this request. For the record, Security team is in favor of the change.
Thank you
Mine Altunay</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='22049#1407510909'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-08-08T15:15:09+00:00">Aug 8, 2014 03:15 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1407510909">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Earlier we decided that OSG will complete its SHA-2 transition after June 2014. Since it is already August,</pre></div><legend>Similar Recent Tickets <small>modified within the last 30 days</small></legend><div id="similar_tickets"><p class="muted">No similar tickets found.</p></div>
